one thing NONE of the conspiracy books had—evidence. The conspiracy books

knowledge unavailable to the general public, I can speculate and come up

I've gone back and forth on this conspiracy allegation and have come to 
conclude that Oswald was indeed the "lone nut" who assassinated JFK. There 
is no doubt that the mafia hated the Kennedy brothers (not without reason), 
but there is also no hard evidence that the mob in fact was involved. Both 
Oswald and Ruby were far too unreliable and unstable to be entrusted with 
such an important assignment. We know that Oswald tried and failed to 
commit one murder (Walker) and later successfully murdered Tippitt. We know 
that he was an unhappy man with delusions of grandeur. And it's close to 
certain that we'll never know more about the assassination than we know 
today.

That the Warren report was incomplete and inaccurate in certain particulars 
goes without saying. LBJ should have given the commission all the time it 
needed to issue a report, but due to geopolitical exigencies he felt the 
need to have its findings ASAP to forestall public outrage against Cuba and 
USSR. 

There was a conspiracy however -- but it took place after the fact. Perhaps

evidence to sustain a dozen theories of this tragic crime. But that doesn't 
make them true. Indeed, the existence of so many theories (many of them 
mutually contradictory) should tell us that they can't all be true, that 
most of them don't withstand scrutiny and ultimately none of them do.
